We are going to make an autoencoder model using EMNIST handwritten alphabet images. 3) [5pt] Show the latent variables of the testset in 2D space.

In[68]:
def encoder(data):
    data = np.asmatrix(data)
    
    encoder1 = data*reg.coefs_[0] + reg.intercepts_[0]
    encoder1 = (np.exp(encoder1) - np.exp(-encoder1))/(np.exp(encoder1) + np.exp(-encoder1))

    encoder2 = encoder1*reg.coefs_[1] + reg.intercepts_[1]
    encoder2 = (np.exp(encoder2) - np.exp(-encoder2))/(np.exp(encoder2) + np.exp(-encoder2))

    encoder3 = encoder2*reg.coefs_[2] + reg.intercepts_[2]
    encoder3 = (np.exp(encoder3) - np.exp(-encoder3))/(np.exp(encoder3) + np.exp(-encoder3))
    
    latent = encoder3*reg.coefs_[3] + reg.intercepts_[3]
    latent = (np.exp(latent) - np.exp(-latent))/(np.exp(latent) + np.exp(-latent))
    
    return np.asarray(latent)

5) [10pt] Generate the fake alphabets decoded from the centroids of each cluster. (The result may not be exactly the same with input image)

In[71]:
c1 = len(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 0,0])
c2 = len(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 1,0])
c3 = len(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 2,0])

c1x, c1y = sum(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 0,0]) /c1 ,sum(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 0,1])/c1
c2x, c2y = sum(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 1,0]) /c2 ,sum(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 1,1])/c2
c3x, c3y = sum(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 2,0]) /c3 ,sum(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 2,1])/c3

def decoder(new_data):
    new_data = np.asmatrix(new_data)
    decoder3 = new_data*reg.coefs_[4] + reg.intercepts_[4]
    decoder3 = (np.exp(decoder3) - np.exp(-decoder3))/(np.exp(decoder3) + np.exp(-decoder3))

    decoder2 = decoder3*reg.coefs_[5] + reg.intercepts_[5]
    decoder2 = (np.exp(decoder2) - np.exp(-decoder2))/(np.exp(decoder2) + np.exp(-decoder2))

    decoder1 = decoder2*reg.coefs_[6] + reg.intercepts_[6]
    decoder1 = (np.exp(decoder1) - np.exp(-decoder1))/(np.exp(decoder1) + np.exp(-decoder1))
    
    reconst = decoder1*reg.coefs_[7] + reg.intercepts_[7]
    reconst = (np.exp(reconst) - np.exp(-reconst))/(np.exp(reconst) + np.exp(-reconst))

    return np.asarray(reconst)

latents = np.array([[[c1x, c1y]], [[c2x, c2y]], [[c3x, c3y]]])

for latent in latents:
    reconst = decoder(latent)
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,7))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.plot(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 0,0],test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 0,1], 'b.', label = 'C0')
    plt.plot(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 1,0],test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 1,1], 'g.', label = 'C1')
    plt.plot(test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 2,0],test_latent[kmeans.labels_ == 2,1], 'r.', label = 'C2')
    plt.scatter(latent[:,0], latent[:,1], c = 'k', marker = 'o', s = 200, label = 'new data')
    plt.title('Latent Space', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xlabel('Z1', fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel('Z2', fontsize = 15)
    plt.legend(loc = 2, fontsize = 12)
    plt.axis('equal')
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    plt.imshow(reconst.reshape(28,28), 'gray')
    plt.title('Generated Fake Image', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
    plt.show()

Solution 4 [15]

We will now discuss an eigenface problem that is dealt with in the classroom.

  • Download eigenfaces

1) [5pt] The shape of "faces" is (32256, 2410). Column of "faces" is images that have been flatten, and 2410 means the number of images. Each column represents each face of Yale university students. The shape of the original image is $168\times192$. Visualize one image, but the face should be $192\times168$, not $168\times 192$.

In[2]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
%matplotlib inline

faces = np.load("./data_files/eigenfaces.npy")
m = 168
n = 192

newface = np.zeros((n,m))
newface = np.reshape(faces[:,0],(m,n)).T

plt.figure(figsize = (10,8))
img = plt.imshow(newface,"gray")
plt.axis("off")
plt.show()

2) [10pt] We want to extract the eigenfaces. First, subtract the average of photos from the original images to build a mean-substracted training dataset. Second, decompose it via SVD. Third, visualize an average face and $U$ with the largest singular value.


In[17]:
avgFace = np.mean(faces, axis = 1)

# Compute eigenfaces on mean-subtracted training data
X = faces - np.tile(avgFace, (faces.shape[1], 1)).T
U, S, VT = np.linalg.svd(X, full_matrices = 0)

fig = plt.figure(figsize = (10,8))
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(121)
img_avg = ax1.imshow(np.reshape(avgFace, (m,n)).T)
img_avg.set_cmap('gray')
plt.axis('off')

ax2 = fig.add_subplot(122)
img_u1 = ax2.imshow(np.reshape(U[:,0], (m,n)).T)
img_u1.set_cmap('gray')
plt.axis('off')

plt.show()
